Exploring Bike Share Data: Visualizing the effects of a global pandemic on San Francisco Bay Area's bike share system¶

by Maren Zoller¶

Investigation Overview¶

In this investigation, I wanted to look at the features influencing bike trip duration in a dataset of bike share data from San Francisco Bay Area's Bay Wheels (formerly Ford GoBike) bike share system. The main focus was on the attributes month, weekday, time of day, and user type. Within the investigation I compared their influence on bike trip duration for the first half year of 2019 and 2020.

Dataset Overview¶

The data consisted of information on 2,530,524 individual bike trips taken between January 2019 and June 2019 and January 2020 and June 2020, such as start and end station location, start and end date and time of the trip, user type, station name, and bike type. To enrich the investigation I used the trip start time to extract month, weekday and hour of the trip, and the latitude and longitude data to add a start city and end city feature to the dataset. Later, I transformed duration seconds to duration minutes, to simplify the trip duration analysis. Also, I performed several cleaning steps to change datatypes and deal with missing data and outliers. All wrangling steps are documented in detail in the exploration notebook.

Distribution of bike trip durations¶

Bike trip durations in the dataset take on a very large range of values, from a few seconds to about a day. Plotted on a logarithmic scale and limited to the first 100 minutes, the distributions of duration minutes are unimodal and heavily right-skewed. In 2020, the number of trips with a duration over 20 minutes is higher than in 2019.

Number of bike trips per month¶

Intuitively, I would have expected the number of trips in 2019 to follow the seasons, i.e. increase with rising temperatures from January to June 2019. Contrary to this, the number of trips is highest in March and April. January, February, May and June all have ca. 5,000 trips less per month.

In 2020, trip numbers in January (ca. 30,000) and February (above 40,000) are higher than in 2019. Starting from March, the effects of the lockdown due to the Covid-19 crisis show in bike trip numbers. From mid-March onwards, Bay Area residents were asked to stay at home, and only leave for essential work, supermarket trips, elderly care, or social-distance friendly outdoor activities (https://techcrunch.com/2020/03/16/bay-area-counties-announce-lockdown-through-april-7/). In April, trips fell below 10,000, then slowly started to recover. In June, it passed the 15,000 trips mark, but is still lower than in March.

Proportion of bike trips per user type¶

In 2019, the majority of bike trips is taken by Bay Wheels subscribers (85%). Subscribers pay a monthly or annual fee to use the bike share system, as opposed to customers, that pay per trip and are charged based on trip duration.

In 2020, Bay Wheels user distribution has shifted. Now 45% of the users are customers, only 55% are customers. This could be explained under the assumption that subscribers primarily use Bay Wheels bikes to commute to work, while customers prefer recreative bike rides. Assuming this, there would be less commuting during the 2020 lockdown, when the Bay Area residents where asked to stay at home and only commute to work if they work in essential jobs. Recreational bike rides could be more prevalent, as people are tired of being stuck indoors, and use bike rides to exercise while staying socially distant.

Number of bike trips by user type per month¶

The distribution of bike trips per user type changed significantly from 2019 to 2020. Can this be tied to the lockdown measures as well? The visualization of bike trips by user type and month does not entirely confirm this.

The ratio of customers to subscribers already changed in January and February. In January, subscriber trips are at almost the same level as in 2019 (ca. 17,000), while customer trips increased from ca. 2,500 in 2019 to ca. 12,500 in 2020. Possibly Bay Wheels has increased its marketing activities for casual trips? In February, ca. 65% of the trips are subscriber trips, in March the ratio is closer to the one seen in the annual comparison. From April onwards, an interesting change is observable: Customer trip numbers recover from the lockdown faster than subscriber trips, there are now more customer than subscriber trips.

Bike trip duration by month¶

When looking at bike trip duration, the seasonal effect that was missing in number of trips is (admittedly only slightly) observable in the 2019 dataset. In a violin plot showing the distribution of bike trip durations of a snapshot of all trips shorter than 1 hour, the median trip duration increases month over month from ca. 9 minutes in January to just above 10 minutes in June.

In 2020, January to March trip durations are very similar to 2019. In the second quarter, the distribution of bike trip durations changes. The median trip duration is longer, and the trip durations are more distributed. In May, median trip duration is at ca. 15 minutes, the third quartile moved from below 20 minutes in the first quarter to ca. 25 minutes in May.

Bike trip duration by day of the week¶

In 2019, there is an observable difference between weekday and weekend trip duration. This is most visible beyond the median (weekdays: ca. 9 minutes, weekends: ca. 11 minutes) and especially the third quartile (weekdays: ca. 13, weekends: ca. 17 minutes).

In 2020, there is still a visible difference between weekday and weekend trip duration, but the distribution of trip lengths changed. The median trip duration increased by only a minute, but the weekdays' third quartile is now at 2019's weekend third quartile, and the weekend third quartile increased to ca. 23 minutes. While the number of longer trips increased, the number of short trips decreased.

Bike trip duration by time of day¶

To visualize bike trip duration by time of day, I decided against violin plots, but used a categorical representation using duration intervals instead. This allows for visualizing all trips, not only the previously chosen duration snapshot.

In 2019, there are very little trips between 11pm and 5 am, trips by hours of the day has a bimodal distribution with one peak at 8am and another, slightly higher one at 5pm. Bike trips up to 10 minutes of length follow the 8am and 5m peaks, with an additional smaller peak at 12pm. Bike trips above 30 minutes of length follow a left-skewed distribution, with a 5pm peak.

In 2020, the two peaks in the distribution are still visible, but the 5pm one is a lot more prominent than the 8 am one. I assume, that 5pm combines a high number of commuter trips with a similarly high number of recreational bike trips. The proportion of longer trips in relation to trips shorter than 20 minutes has increased. Judging from the visualization, Bay Wheels bikes are largely used for commuting to and from work, and following the lockdown measures shorter commuting trips decreased and recreational longer trips increased.

Bike trip duration by user type¶

In 2019, the distribution of bike trip duration by user type is visibly different. The median trip duration for subscribers is around 9 minutes, for customers at ca. 15 minutes. The customer trip duration curve is flatter and more distributed than the subscriber one, and shows an interesting step downwards at 30 minutes. This is potentially related to Bay Wheels pricing system, that charges customers 2 USD for the first 30 minutes and 2 USD more for each additional 15 minutes.

In 2020, an interesting change in distributions can be observed. The subscriber curve stays nearly the same, but shows an increase in trips above 20 minutes and an increased median trip duration. The customer distribution now resembles the subscriber one, with a lower median trip duration than in 2019 caused by an extreme increase in shorter trips below 20 minutes. The number of customer trips increased in all categories, also the longer trips, but no category shows a greater increase than the one below 5 minutes. While I can not prove this with the data at hand, I suspect the overall increase in customer trips to be related to Bay area residents looking for social-distance friendly recreational activities, and the increase in trips shorter than 5 minutes with first-time customers testing out if Bay Wheels works for them.

Bike trip duration by user type and month¶

As previously seen, number of bike trips by user type and month had largely different distributions in 2019 and 2020. Is this difference also visible in bike trip duration? To investigate this question, average bike trip duration by month and user type are visualized in a bar chart, with error bars representing variability.

In 2019, mean subscriber trip duration is at a similar level across all investigated months, increasing from ca. 10 to ca. 11 minutes from January to June. Customer trips are on average about 15 minutes longer, and have a higher trip duration variability. Average trip duration is longest in March.

In the first quarter of 2020, mean subscriber trip duration is around 12 minutes long, mean customer trip duration decreased by ca. 10 minutes, and increases incrementally month over month. Potentially, this is due to the increase in short customer trips, that was observable in the previous visualization. Customer trips still have a higher variability than subscriber trips, but the length of the error bars decreased. In April and May, mean customer trip duration increases to a slightly higher level than in the same months in 2019, mean subscriber trip duration increases to 17 minutes in April and over 20 minutes in May. In June, the mean trip length starts to decrease again for both user types. Subscriber trips are now on average 15 minutes long, customer trips 20 minutes.

Bike trip duration by start station location¶

The previous visualizations showed the impact of user type, month, week day and hour of the day on bike trip duration in 2019 and 2020. To close the presentation, I am using a map visualization of trips up to 60 minutes length to compare the trip duration per station in 2019 and 2020. This visualization confirms, that the change in trip duration from 2019 to 2020 is not a regional phenomenon, but visible in all 3 regions offering Bay Wheels bikes. In 2019, the majority of trip duration markers is violet or blue, representing trips below 20 minutes. There are less turquoise and green markers (trip length above 30 minutes) to be found, most of them at the outskirts of the three cities. For 2020, there are a lot more green and even some yellow markers visible. The start stations for these longer trips are both found at outskirts and city centers.
